% bench_journal_write.trx -- journal-write hot path throughput.
%
% Each inner iteration does:  save  put-on-local-dict  restore
% so save_data() must journal one entry per iter (the entry's
% save_level (0) is below curr_save_level (1) inside the save scope).
%
% This is exactly the path the Phase 1 short-circuits added a check to:
% Save::save_data starts with `if (is_global(off)) return nullptr;`
% which costs one address-range comparison per call -- always FALSE in
% this benchmark since the dict is local.  PF2 quantifies that cost.
%
% Counter: N iters -> N save_data() calls -> N journal entries.
% Plus N save+restore pairs -- those touch the save journal stack
% (save() / restore()) but the per-put cost is still the dominant
% portion of the work.

/N 1000000 def
32 dict /D exch def
% Pre-populate one key at BASE so the put inside save mutates an
% existing entry whose save_level is below current.
D 0 0 put

N {
    save
    D 0 1 put
    restore
} repeat
